<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Tibi Rejects Demand for 'Arafat Commitment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Tibi Rejects Demand for 'Arafat Commitment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2405193094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1900 GMT 24 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2405193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ahmad al-Tibi, Yasir 'Arafat's adviser, today 
rejected the demand that the PLO head present a letter in which 
he pledges to honor the agreement with Israel. He also lashed 
at the demand that Prime Minister Rabin send the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] into the Gaza Strip. Dr. al-Tibi demanded that 
the interim period be shortened because he believes five years 
is too long a period during which to form the permanent 
solution. According to him, circumstances on the ground will 
force the parties to immediately begin negotiating the permanent 
solution. 
  Speaking at a seminar on the peace process at the Ben-Gurion 
University in Beersheba, Dr. al-Tibi said that the Palestinian 
goal is to establish an independent state, the capital of which 
will be East Jerusalem. According to him, there are cabinet 
ministers who support the establishment of an independent 
Palestinian state. He believes that the settlements can be kept 
in place and, after they are evacuated by the settlers, they 
could be populated by the Palestinian refugees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

