<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Saddam Launches `Purge' Against al-Duri Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saddam Launches `Purge' Against al-Duri Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2405153194 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 21 May 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> PM2405153194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Saddam Expels Senior Officials and </F>
Military Figures Who Come from 'Izzat al-Duri's Village"] 
  [Text] London, AL-HAYAH -- Iraqi opposition quarters have 
stressed that President Saddam Husayn has launched a purge 
campaign among the regime's ranks, focusing on prominent 
figures, all of whom come from al-Duri (the village of al-Duri 
is near the village of al-'Awjah in Tikrit, the president's 
birthplace) -- from where 'Izzat al-Duri, his deputy in the 
presidency, the Armed Forces command, and the ruling Ba'th Party 
-- comes. In a statement distributed in London and a copy of 
which AL-HAYAH has received, the Free Iraqi Council said that 
Saddam accused a number of senior officials from al-Duri of 
conspiring against the regime. They are: Tali' al-Duri, 
military governor general; 'Abd-al-Rahman al-Duri, director of 
public security and former member of the Ba'th Party Regional 
Command, who was in charge of the Mosul organization in the 
past; Khadr al-Duri, former deputy of former intelligence chief 
Barzan al-Tikriti, Saddam's half-brother; and Sabir al-Duri, 
former intelligence chief. 
  The council's statement said that 'Abd-al-Rahman al-Duri's 
family has been expelled from its home in the exclusive 
al-Mansur area, west of Baghdad, and that the house has been 
turned into offices for one of the Ba'th Party's organizations. 
  Furthermore, a number of Army officers and party officials 
have been pensioned off. Some of them are being investigated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

