<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Forces Announce Anti-`Extremist' Campaign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Forces Announce Anti-`Extremist' Campaign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2405191594 Cairo AL-SHA'B in Arabic 17 May 94 p 7 </F>
<F P=103> NC2405191594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo AL-SHA'B </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Ala' al-Bahhar] </F>
  [Text] The security service departments will launch 
wide-scale campaigns over the next two weeks in an attempt to 
arrest many members of the militant extremist groups. The 
security departments estimate the number of group members at 
5,000. 
  A ranking security official has told AL-SHA'B that in the 
next stage the security service will step up armed confrontation 
in Asyut. He said a timetable had been drawn up by the interior 
ministry to liquidate the leaders of the extremist groups inside 
and outside the prisons. He added that the armed confrontation 
operations will last for a while. He admitted that the security 
service has failed to properly monitor the militant elements 
within the extremist groups. 
  The official said that the interior ministry had covered up 
this failure by announcing that 98 leading extremists were 
captured even though most of them were detained arbitrarily. 
Some of the detainees now in custody of the state security 
intelligence will appear on television and in the papers and be 
repentant as former members of extremist groups. 
  The security official added that the announcement on the 
latest organization was prompted by the political leadership to 
confront the activities of the lawyers association, which is 
calling for an investigation into the killing of lawyer 
'Abd-al-Harith Madani. The interior ministry has said that 
Madani was a link between the Islamic Group's leaders inside and 
outside the prisons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

