Daily Report 
<DATE1>  20 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Stresses Subsidy Reform To Be Gradual </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Stresses Subsidy Reform To Be Gradual </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005141594 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1030 GMT 20 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [First Friday prayers sermon by President 'Ali Akbar </F>
Hashemi-Rafsanjani in Tehran on 20 May -- recorded] 
  [Excerpts] In the name of God, the compassionate, the 
merciful. [passage omitted] In the first sermon we will continue 
the discussion on social justice. [passage omitted] In last 
year's sermons I spoke about resources; but less was said about 
expenditures last year. So in the first sermon this year we 
spoke about it. I think I should list a few more in the next 
few sermons. In the last sermon I referred to subsidies as one 
of the areas of realizing justice in the distribution of the 
treasury and the government's financial resources. Briefly, 
what I meant was that there were unjust subsidies left from the 
distant past, that some injustices have been eradicated, and 
there are important areas left. I referred to fuel and bread 
and some other items [subsidies] which are still unfair. Of 
course, I explained then that since they are very important and 
have a great effect on life, one cannot take instantaneous 
decisions about them. It needs planning, and problems arising 
in conjunction with removing subsidies should be considered. 
Therefore, we will keep them until our plan is ready. 
  In the second five-year plan there are certain indications 
for this to happen in five years, but in our view even five 
years are not enough. It needs at least 10 years for us to 
remove the inequities which exist in fuel and bread consumption 
in the society. But then, some media rushed in and said that 
speech smelled of new price rises. It is not so. I stressed 
then that it will be done with planning. God willing, part of 
those plans are in the Majles and other parts will be prepared 
later. Our people should not worry about rash and quick 
measures in these sensitive times. We will act cautiously. I 
said then that some actions would arouse resentment against the 
government because they might put severe pressure on the people. 
Therefore, such tasks will be carried out with prudence. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

