<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> India </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Denies Receiving DPRK Food Request </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Minister Denies Receiving DPRK Food Request </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2305141494 Hong Kong AFP in English 1231 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2305141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] New Delhi, May 23 (AFP) -- Jyoti Basu, chief 
minister of the Indian state of West Bengal, denied on Monday 
[24 May] press reports that North Korea had requested food aid 
during his recent visit to Pyongyang. Basu, a member of the 
politburo of the Communist Party of India (Marxist), said in a 
statement that the reports that North Korean officials had asked 
him to arrange emergency shipments of rice from India were 
"absolutely baseless." 
  "I had talks with several leaders of (North Korea), 
including 
the prime minister," said Basu, who visited North Korea from May 
7-14. "But no one made such a request to me. 
  "On the contrary, I was impressed by their economic 
development, construction work and their confidence to meet any 
situation," he said. "The news item is obviously intended to 
show (North Korea) in a bad light." 
  Basu, who heads India's sole communist state government, has 
been in power in West Bengal for 17 years. 

</TEXT>

