<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Israeli-Palestinian Agricultural Trade Talks Begin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Israeli-Palestinian Agricultural Trade Talks Begin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2505160094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1500 GMT 25 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2505160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Israeli-Palestinian negotiations on agricultural 
trade arrangements between Israel and the autonomy have begun at 
Tel Aviv's Carlton Hotel. 
  Israel's delegation is headed by Agriculture Ministry 
Director General Yehonatan Bashi, and the Palestinian delegation 
is led by Khalid al-Qidrah, a PLO leader in the Gaza Strip, who 
recently arrived from Tunis. The talks are aimed at working out 
procedures for agricultural trade between Israel and the 
autonomy and measures to make ascertain the quality of the 
agricultural produce entering Israel. There is special concern 
about the use of pesticides and the health of the animals in the 
autonomy. Our correspondent notes that even before the talks 
started it was decided that mutual agricultural trade will take 
place only if the standards used in Israel are upheld in the 
autonomy. Our correspondent recalls that under the autonomy 
agreement, the borders will be opened to free passage of 
agricultural produce, except for five sectors, in which 
temporary quotas have been introduced. These are: tomatoes, 
potatoes, cucumbers, eggs, and spring chickens. There is no 
doubt that hoof-and-mouth disease, which has recently been 
uncovered in Jericho, and ways to prevent it from spreading, 
will undoubtedly come up in the talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

