<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Difficulties Facing Palestinian Authority Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Difficulties Facing Palestinian Authority Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2605045694 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 24 May 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> NC2605045694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "Difficulties That Must Be Overcome"] </F>
  [Text] Observers currently agree that just as they 
expected a few weeks ago, the process of transferring power to 
the Palestinian National Authority will not be easy, 
particularly in light of the bad economic conditions prevailing 
in the occupied territories. 
  The process as a whole is considered an extremely important 
historical turning point. The Palestinian people are aware of 
their duty to ensure the success of this process, because the 
cost of failure, God forbid, would be extremely tragic. 
  The Palestinians' task at present is to establish the organs 
and cadres of the Palestinian Authority, on the one hand, and to 
keep the wheels of government turning, on the other, in order to 
provide the necessary services to the citizens and create jobs 
for tens of thousands of unemployed workers. This demands the 
establishment of industrial and agricultural projects in the 
areas of the transitional authority to absorb these workers as 
soon as possible. 
  There is no doubt that ensuring security and peace is 
considered one of the main challenges and difficult tests facing 
the Palestinians. In view of these difficulties and obstacles, 
the Palestinians must make greater efforts and sacrifices to 
overcome them. The states that have pledged to provide economic 
aid to the Palestinians are called upon to fulfill their 
commitments. Numerous dangers are threatening peace. Time is 
definitely one of the factor endangering the peace process and 
Palestinian aspirations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60515 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes102dd_94016" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-102 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Columnist Derides 'Arafat's Jihad Call </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Columnist Derides 'Arafat's Jihad Call </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2505155394 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 24 May 94 p 9 </F>
<F P=103> PM2505155394 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by 'Abd-al-Rahman al-Rashid: "Abu-'Ammar's </F>
Jihad!!"] 
  [Excerpts] Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin is very 
angry because Palestinian President Yasir 'Arafat has declared 
jihad against the Israelis from South Africa. We wish to 
reassure him here that 'Arafat's jihad call will not achieve for 
him more than he can achieve at the negotiating table. 
Abu-'Ammar ['Arafat] did not achieve much when he was calling 
for jihad just a few miles away from Palestine, let alone doing 
that from Johannesburg at the far end of Africa. [passage 
omitted] 
  In the view of the majority, jihad is no longer jihad 
because 
most battles are between brothers, for personal vendettas, or 
foreign battles fought on Islamic territory. With the weakening 
of the leadership and its credibility, the word jihad has become 
weaker. Rabin, therefore, should rest assured that Abu-'Ammar's 
call will not move the people of South Africa, just as it did 
not move others. 
  The real jihad was that of the unarmed people who risked 
their lives to target the head of an Israeli soldier with their 
stones. What came before was just military operations by regular 
armies. 
  Even the other organizations which declare jihad in the name 
of Islam, have two problems. The first is that, like 
Abu-'Ammar, they make the call from distant places like Tehran, 
and the second is that they declare jihad as a part of the same 
organization which brings them together with communist groups at 
the same table. They cannot carry out their jihad from a place 
a thousand miles away nor can they call what they are doing 
jihad when they seek the assistance of communists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

