<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Split Reported in Opposition's Military Arm </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Split Reported in Opposition's Military Arm </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2505102394 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 21 May 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> PM2505102394 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "New Split in Sudanese Opposition's </F>
Military Arm"] 
  [Excerpts] London, AL-HAYAH -- A group of military members 
of the "Sudanese Army Military Command" organization, the 
military arm of the opposition Democratic National Grouping, has 
announced the dismissal of its leadership and the formation of a 
new leadership, "because the present leadership has not carried 
out any military action against the regime over the past five 
years -- which has caused it to lose a great deal and prompted 
many people to abandon it." 
  A statement issued by the group and distributed in Cairo 
yesterday, a copy of which AL-HAYAH has received, said that the 
leadership of retired Lieutenant General Fathi Ahmad 'Ali, the 
Army's former commander in chief, "has not moved from the 
theorization stage to the implementation stage -- which has 
adversely affected its performance, reputation, and status 
inside and outside the country. In fact it has focused 
primarily on political action and ignored its main duty, thus 
losing its credibility and status in opposition action." 
[passage omitted] 
  The officers decided to "dismiss Lt. Gen. Fathi and Major 
General al-Hadi Bushra (the third man in the organization) and 
to form a new leadership committee after consulting with the 
organization's offices in Europe and Britain." The breakaway 
group stressed that it "has nothing to do with any agreements, 
decisions, or statements issued by the leadership. And we 
stress our commitment to the principles and charter of the 
Democratic National Grouping" [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

