<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Premier Vows Action To Restore Democracy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Premier Vows Action To Restore Democracy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2105181294 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1710 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2105181294 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Khartoum, 21 May (MENA) -- Former Sudanese Prime 
Minister al-Sadiq al-Mahdi has criticized the present political 
practices in Sudan, calling for democratic elections to let the 
Sudanese people decide who will govern them. 
  In his 'Id al-Adha sermon at the al-Ansar Mosque in 
(?Udinbawi), Omdurman, today al-Mahdi said that the situation in 
Sudan is the worst it has ever been, noting that he will take 
serious action to restore democracy in the country. 
  Al-Mahdi pointed out that the government-appointed 
parliament 
does not fit into this category because it is appointed by the 
authority that is supposed to be accountable to it. 
  He criticized the government's economic policies, 
particularly the profit-sharing system, which he described as 
the most repulsive crime ever against the Sudanese economy. 
  The former prime minister criticized the government's 
management of alms and its establishment of the Alms Department, 
saying that most of the money is being spent on the employees of 
that department. 

</TEXT>

