<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Official: Al-Bid Appreciative of Mubarak's Stance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    YSP Official: Al-Bid Appreciative of Mubarak's Stance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2505124394 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 24 May 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2505124394 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Faysal Makram, Iqbal 'Abdallah, Zaki Shihab, and </F>
Muhammad 'Allam: "North Preparing To Attack Hadhramaut"] 
  [Excerpts] Sanaa, Aden, Cairo -- Neutral sources said 
yesterday that northern forces were continuing their pressure on 
southern forces, that they had already seized Shabwah 
Governorate, which is rich in oil, and that their next step will 
be to penetrate Hadhramaut Governorate, birthplace of Yemeni 
Socialist Party [YSP] Secretary General 'Ali Salim al-Bid. 
[passage omitted] 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-'Aziz al-Dali, member of the YSP Political 
Bureau, has told AL-HAYAH that meetings will be held in a few 
days between officials of the new state and the Egyptian 
Government. He pointed out that an envoy from Aden will 
tomorrow submit a request to join the Arab League. Al-Dali 
said: "'Ali Salim al-Bid and the Yemeni people in the south are 
most appreciative of President Husni Mubarak's position on the 
Yemeni crisis," describing it as a "courageous position." 
  Last week Mubarak held Yemeni President 'Ali Salih 
responsible for the continuation of the fighting and urged him 
to observe an unconditional cease-fire and to initiate a 
dialogue. He also described the northern forces' presence in 
the south as "occupation." Al-Dali added: "Al-Bid would not 
have barked on the secession step without consulting with a 
number of Arab leaders. He did not name them. He interpreted 
the Arab silence about the the question of recognizing the state 
as "positive and aimed at studying the situation." He expressed 
his belief that "Arab recognition will take place within days." 
He noted that "President Mubarak, United Arab Emirates 
President Shaykh Zayid Bin-Sultan Al Nuhayyan, and most Arab 
states stressed that the continuation of the war means 
destroying unity." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

