<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Rejects Peres' Statement on Normalization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Daily Rejects Peres' Statement on Normalization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2605082194 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0445 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2605082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Press review] </F>
  [Text] Under the headline "Peres' Statement and the Israeli 
illusion," AL-BA'TH says: The Israeli officials' contradictory 
statements on peace and the terms of reference of the peace 
process continue. The latest of these statements was made by 
Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres. Yesterday he asked Syria to 
normalize its relations with Israel, and emphasized that the 
normalization process should have begun with the negotiation 
process. 
  AL-BA'TH adds: This means that Peres wants normalization 
before the Israeli withdrawal from the occupied land. It is not 
ruled out that Israel wants normalization of relations while our 
land is under occupation. The statements by several Israeli 
officials, especially Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin and Peres 
emphasize this fact. 
  It says: In their statements, Rabin, Peres, and others have 
so far not referred to full withdrawal from the Golan, but they 
always and only emphasize withdrawal in the Golan. This 
emphasizes that Israel wants the peace process to entrench its 
occupation of Arab land, and then the Arabs should normalize 
relations with it. By this, Israel would have both peace and 
land. This is what Israel seeks through deeds, not words. 
  The newspaper stresses that these statements do not benefit 
the peace process, but are directed against it. The Israelis 
are mistaken if they believe Syria may give up its declared 
policy on the peace process. 
  The newspaper says: Syria's acceptance to participate in the 
peace process stemmed from its clear principles and constants, 
based on implementation of resolutions of international 
legitimacy and the land-for-peace principle. 
  The newspaper stresses that full and comprehensive Israeli 
withdrawal from the occupied Arab territories is unnegotiable as 
a condition for continuing the peace process with all its 
details. 
  The newspaper speaks about the Israeli policy which depends 
on maneuvers and evasion of the requisites of the peace process, 
and says: That policy is totally rejected by Syria. Syria 
always emphasizes that the basic condition for achieving a just 
and comprehensive peace is Israel's full withdrawal from our 
occupied land. Short of this, the peace process will continue 
to be stalemated. 
  The newspaper warns against the Israeli maneuvering policy 
because it will lead the peace process to a dead end, which is 
what Israel seeks. 
  AL-BA'TH concludes by saying: Israel should remember that 
the conflict is continuing and resolving it will not be easy. 
It is time for Israel to be aware that there will be no peace, 
security, and stability in the region while our Arab land is 
occupied. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

