  [Text] Pakistan decided to submit a peace plan to Afghan 
leaders next week during the reopening of its mission in 
Afghanistan. This was stated by Foreign Minister Sardar Asif 
Ahmad Ali in Islamabad yesterday. He said the peace plan has 
been formulated on the basis of proposals by influential Afghan 
leaders, which provides a common basis for establishing peace in 
the war- ravaged country of Afghanistan. The foreign minister 
said that he will visit Kabul on 25 May for this purpose. He 
said that he held talks with Saudi Foreign Minister Prince Sa'ud 
al-Faysal, Crown Prince Turki, and leaders of other countries 
after receiving requests from Afghan leaders. He said that he 
held a similar exchange of views with UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Ghali to secure his assistance in establishing peace in 
Afghanistan. 
  Sardar Asif Ahmad Ali also announced that Pakistan will 
establish a mission in (Hayat) and a consulate in Mazar-e 
Sharif. This indicates the importance Pakistan attaches to 
these places, which link Pakistan with Central Asian countries. 

