<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Discusses 'Arafat Behavior, Legal Decree </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres Discusses 'Arafat Behavior, Legal Decree </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2605074694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 0405 GMT 26 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2605074694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres, who is visiting the 
United States, told our correspondent Arye Golan that 'Arafat is 
facing severe pressure from the Palestinian peace opponents, 
which can perhaps explain his remarks regarding the Quraish 
Tribe and the cancellation of the Israeli laws in the autonomy. 
  [Begin recording] [Peres] 'Arafat has no legislative 
authority and no authority to cancel existing laws. So things 
are published in the newspapers, I would prefer the newspaper 
reports to also agree with the spirit of the Declaration of 
Principles. 
  [Golan] What can we learn about 'Arafat and his behavior 
from this? 
  [Peres] I am not a psychologist, and I do not think I should 
comment on the person himself. I can only tell you what he told 
me, namely, that he is facing a very strong opposition and that 
he is struggling to implement his policy. He told me, for 
example, that the entire Johannesburg mosque affair transpired 
during a heated argument with the Iranians, who accused him of 
proceeding with Israel while the latter is violating the 
agreement. 'Arafat claims he said that if Israel violates the 
agreement he will violate it himself, just as Muhammad violated 
the agreement after the Quraish Tribe violated it. 
  I do not want, however, to serve as 'Arafat's advocate, it 
is 
not my duty. I also do not want to hand out grades. I am 
conducting negotiations rather than dealing with graphological 
analysis or psychoanalysis. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

