<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Delegation Seeks Expanded Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Delegation Seeks Expanded Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2605113694 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2605113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In the context of expanding political-economic 
cooperation between the Islamic Republic of Iran and South 
Africa, the first South African political-economic delegation 
headed by their Foreign Ministry director general arrived in 
Tehran for talks on defining ways of cooperation between the two 
countries. 
  Members of the 13-man delegation, which includes a number of 
government and private sector officials, this morning attended a 
seminar on the expansion of economic relations at Iran's 
Chambers of Trade, Industry, and Mines and announced that they 
were prepared to expand trade and economic relations with Iran. 
  According to our correspondent: Shayk-ol-elslam [name as 
heard], our country's deputy foreign minister in charge of 
Afro-Arab affairs told the meeting the fact that the Islamic 
Republic of Iran was the first country to reopen its embassy in 
South Africa after the end of apartheid indicated Iranian 
interest in cooperation with South Africa in all fields. 
  Referring to oil, industry, and trade as fields for the 
expansion of economic relations between the two countries, he 
called on industrialists and businessmen to take into account 
the common views of the political and economic officials in the 
two countries and start efforts toward the expansion of 
cooperation. 
  During their stay in Iran, the South African delegation will 
meet economic representatives of the government and the private 
sector as well as industrialists. 

</TEXT>

