<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-103 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  26 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Reportedly Drafting State Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Reportedly Drafting State Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2605184794 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1700 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2605184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with French jurist (Jean Marc Vareau) by Eldad </F>
Beck in Paris; date not given -- recorded, in French with Hebrew 
subtitles; translated from the Hebrew] 
  [Text] PLO Chief Yasir 'Arafat has launched an effort to 
arrange the drafting of a Palestinian constitution. The Channel 
2 news department has learned that to that end, he conveyed a 
draft document for the perusal of a French lawyer. According to 
the document, Jerusalem is the capital of an independent 
Palestine. Our Paris-based correspondent Eldad Beck heard the 
details of the constitution from the French jurist: 
  [Begin recording] [(Vareau)] He assured me that he would 
honor human rights; that the provisional constitution would 
ensure the separation of powers, the independence of legal 
institutions; that it will not be an Islamic state; that there 
would be genuine equality between men and women, between Muslims 
and non-Muslims; that Christians and Israelis would enjoy 
freedom of worship and education. At that point, to prove to me 
that it would be a state of law, he handed me something that had 
just been prepared -- a proposal for a transitional constitution 
to be used before the state is fully sovereign. 
  [Beck] Then 'Arafat plainly told you that this text would be 
the Palestinian state's constitution? 
  [(Vareau)] We agreed that since they have physical authority 
over a defined territory, since they rightfully control a 
legitimate police force, and since they have the right to pass 
their own laws, they are practically a sovereign state. That 
text plainly indicates that Jerusalem is the capital of 
Palestine, but the Palestinian government that will be elected, 
that will be appointed before parliament is convened, will be 
able to decide on a capital in another location in Palestine. 
Thus Jerusalem will be a constitutional demand, while the 
actual capital will be either Gaza or Jericho. [end recording] 
  [An announcer-read report later in the newscast adds: "In 
reaction to the report about 'Arafat's plan to draft a 
constitution for the Palestinian state, Prime Minister Yitzhaq 
Rabin said a few minutes ago: `It is all talk, just like the 
radio program.'"] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

