<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   PLO Said Not Yet Decided on Weapons Collection </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PLO Said Not Yet Decided on Weapons Collection </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2605185794 Paris Radio Monte Carlo in Arabic 1700 GMT 26 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2605185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris Radio Monte Carlo </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In wake of recent reports about the possibility of 
starting to collect weapons from Palestinians in the autonomy 
areas soon, Fatah Central Committee Member 'Abas Zaki said 
during a dialogue with the press in Damascus today that the 
Palestinian command has not yet made a decision to collect 
weapons from the Palestinians in the autonomy areas, especially 
since there is an armed enemy and weapons are in the hands of 
the settlers. 
  Zaki said a PLO delegation will visit Damascus for talks 
with 
the Syrian officials and the Palestinian opposition. However, 
he did not say when the visit will take place. 
  Zaki, a moderate opposer of the Palestinian-Israeli 
agreement, arrived in Damascus yesterday and held talks today 
with Nayif Hawatimah, secretary general of the Democratic Front 
for the Liberation of Palestine [DFLP], and will also meet with 
George Habash, the secretary general of the Popular Front for 
the Liberation of Palestine, and Ahmad Jibril, secretary general 
of the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General 
Command. 
  After meeting Zaki today, Hawatimah said the DFLP and all 
the 
other nationalist and democratic forces will pursue the struggle 
against the occupation and against the settlers who carry 
120,000 weapons. Hawatimah said: That's why we rejected all 
calls seeking to disarm the sons of the intifada. Hawatimah 
warned the Palestinian police against crossing the red lines. 

</TEXT>

