<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Iryani on Civil War, YSP, Solution to Crisis </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Iryani on Civil War, YSP, Solution to Crisis </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says Contacts With YSP Under Way </H4>

<F P=102> PM2605143194 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 26 May 94 pp 
1, 4 </F>

<F P=103> PM2605143194 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Reports by 'Abdallah Hammudah and Lutfi Shatarah in London, </F>
Najib Sadiq in Aden, and AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT bureaus in Sanaa and 
Cairo: "Sanaa Leans Towards Negotiations and Aden Fights to 
Regain Shabwah"] 
  [Excerpts] A new tendency has appeared in the North Yemeni 
command in Sanaa indicating "a willingness to start a dialogue 
with Aden" with the aim of stopping the fighting between the 
northern and southern forces as a result of which 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid, secretary general of the Yemeni Socialist Party [YSP], 
proclaimed the Democratic Republic of Yemen in the south, ending 
the four-year old unity between the two parts of Yemen. 
  That tendency was reflected in a statement by Dr. 
'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani, planning and development minister and 
member of the General Committee (Political Bureau) of the 
General People's Congress [GPC], who said that "contacts are 
underway between YSP leaders and the government of Sanaa to 
agree on holding a dialogue." [passage omitted] 
  AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT has learned from sources of arms dealers 
in 
Europe that Jordan has expressed willingness to purchase arms on 
behalf of the northern forces command in Sanaa after numerous 
states banned the sale of arms to Sanaa and Aden as long as the 
war between their forces in Yemen continued. The sources said 
that Jordan acted in the same way to purchase arms for Iraq 
throughout the years of war between Iraq and Iran. [passage 
omitted] 
  While the intensity of the battles generally eased after 
fierce fighting on the Kharaz-Bab el Mandeb front on the western 
axis the day before yesterday, the most important battle 
yesterday was in the Shabwah Governorate. Shabwah Governor 
Ahmad Bin-Farid al-Suraymah has told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that the 
southern forces have captured the northern part of 'Ataq, the 
capital of Shabwah, and that fighting was raging in the 
southwestern part of the town. 
  In an exclusive telephone statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT via 
satellite from the battlefield, the Shabwah governor said that 
the remnants of the northern forces consisting of a Republican 
Guard brigade, a shock brigade, a paratroopers brigade, and the 
6th Brigade "withdrew from parts of the town after their 
soldiers looted people's property and acted like thieves." 
  He confirmed that the southern forces recaptured several 
towns including al-Sa'id and al-Musayni'ah after inflicting 
losses on the northern forces including hundreds of casualties. 
He emphasized that "the liberation of the Shabwah Governorate 
will be completed within two days at the most." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-60647 </DOCNO>
