<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shohat Views Economic Agreement With Palestinians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shohat Views Economic Agreement With Palestinians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2305131694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 23 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2305131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Finance Minister Avraham Shohat today told members 
of the Knesset Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee that the 
economic agreement signed with the Palestinians is based on 
intentions to have economic cooperation and that it may 
contribute to the development of ties between Israel and the 
Near East countries. The agreement is good for us and for the 
Palestinians, and it leaves Israel in control over the main 
issues pertaining to our interests, the finance minister 
asserted. 
  Our correspondent Eytan Almog reports that replying to a 
question by Likud chairman Binyamin Netanyahu, the finance 
minister said there are no signs of a Palestinian migration from 
the territories to the Arab countries as a result of the closure. 
  Replying to a question by Beni Begin, Shohat said there is 
no 
need for a Palestinian currency seeing that the agreement does 
not provide for a central Palestinian bank or an independent 
Palestinian economic system. 
  Former Finance Minister Moshe Nisim sharply attacked the 
agreement, saying that as a consequence, compensation will have 
to be paid to Israeli farmers and that industrialists claim it 
will lead to the dismissal of 9,000 workers. Nisim added that 
this is not an economic, but a political and nationalist 
agreement. Minister Shohat replied that the Palestinians signed 
the agreement for economic reasons. They are being subjected to 
heavy pressures by the Arab countries for having signed the 
agreement, and this proves that theirs were economic rather than 
political considerations, the finance minister said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

