<H3> <TI>   Kakh Activists Remanded in Administrative Detention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kakh Activists Remanded in Administrative Detention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2305125094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1200 GMT 23 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2305125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The commander of the Central Command decided to 
extend the administrative detention of Kakh activists No'am 
Federman and Ben-Tziyon Gubstein by another three months, our 
correspondent Aviv Bushinsky has learned. The two were 
scheduled to be released in two days, but the Hasharon prison 
authorities received an order to remand them in custody. Our 
correspondent has learned that both the detainees and the police 
were surprised by the news, and the detainees intend to appeal 
it. 
  The High Court of Justice rejected the appeal of Gil'on 
Ben-Sa'id, a Qiryat Arba' settler and a major in the reserves, 
whose weapon was confiscated after the massacre in Hebron. Our 
correspondent Mira Amsalem reports that the judges ruled that 
the commander of the Central Command's decision to confiscate 
his weapon was appropriate and was based on reliable information 
whereby Ben-Sa'id had previously been involved in violent 
activities. Our correspondent points out that a restraining 
order has been in effect against Ben-Sa'id banning him from the 
boundaries of Hebron. 

</TEXT>

