<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beilin Urges Merger of Meretz, Labor Parties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beilin Urges Merger of Meretz, Labor Parties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2305105094 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 23 May 94 p A9 </F>
<F P=103> TA2305105094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by party affairs correspondent Yerah Tal] </F>
  [Excerpts] Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi Beilin called 
yesterday for the immediate establishment of a new Israeli 
democratic party to be created by a merger between Meretz and 
Labor. Speaking before the Labor's dovish Mashov circle, Beilin 
said that the move should begin at the Histadrut labor 
federation by merging Hayim Ramon's list with Labor and should 
extend to all the other activities by the parties. 
  "We would have an 80-percent majority in the Histadrut and 
56 
Knesset seats, which would make us as dominant as the Labor 
Movement was at its peak," Beilin said. According to him, past 
differences between Meretz and Labor no longer exist. He added 
that a merger now would allow Ramon to implement all the reforms 
he has planned as Histadrut secretary general, with Labor 
assisting him. [passage omitted] 
  Knesset Member Ya'el Dayan rejected Beilin's idea, saying 
that a merger is possible only between Meretz and the Labor 
doves. Any other combination would only cause a rift, she said. 
She believes there is room for such a merger in the Histadrut, 
but talk of a merger on the parliamentary level is premature. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English at 1000 GMT on 23 May 
carries a report by Dani Gur-Arye with the following "fast and 
furious" political reactions to the offer: "Meretz leader 
Shulamit Aloni said the two parties have much in common, but 
also many differences. She said it is still early to determine 
if such a union is plausible. Yosi Sarid said the Meretz 
parties should unite first, before considering a union with 
Labor." The report adds that "Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
criticized Beilin for the remark, saying his timing, following 
the Histadrut elections, could not have been worse. Rabin said 
a joint Labor-Meretz party would alienate middle-of-the-road 
voters. Without the support of those voters, he said, the new 
Israeli democratic party would be destined for the opposition."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

