<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Beilin Welcomes British Lifting of Arms Embargo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Beilin Welcomes British Lifting of Arms Embargo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2605153094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 1500 GMT 26 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2605153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Israel has welcomed the British Government's 
decision to lift the arms embargo. Deputy Foreign Minister Yosi 
Beilin in an interview with our reporter Jack Katzenell 
described the lifting of the embargo as a very important 
decision. 
  [Begin recording] [Beilin] Of course, it has a symbolic 
effect, but it has also a very realistic impact because it will 
enable us to participate in bids of selling arms to Britain, 
which will include British components, and that can happen only 
when the embargo is lifted, and when the British can sell us 
those components. 
  [Katzenell] So, do you think that this embargo, which has 
lasted 12 years, has it done Israel a great deal of harm, or has 
it been mainly a kind of slap in the face, something moral or 
symbolic? 
  [Beilin] Both. This embargo was decided upon during the war 
in Lebanon in 1982. It was a European decision, and only 
Britain decided to continue the embargo. In our visits to 
London and the meetings with British officials, we raised this 
issue. I raised it with Secretary Hurd exactly two weeks ago, 
and I said to him that it is really inexplicable to continue the 
embargo after the agreement which has been signed between us and 
the PLO, and against the background of the development towards 
this in the Middle East, and I believe that those talks with the 
British helped us in putting an end to this embargo. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

