<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Reserves Increased 28 Percent Since 1990 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Energy Reserves Increased 28 Percent Since 1990 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2405115694 Cairo MENA in Arabic 0900 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2405115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Cairo, 24 May (MENA) -- Petroleum Minister Hamdi 
al-Banbi has stated that Egyptian oil and natural gas reserves 
increased in the past four years by 1.7 billion barrels, at a 
rate of 28 percent of the reserve in 1990. We now have a 
reserve of 7.7 billion barrels, he said. 
  Al-Banbi pointed out in a statement today that the increase 
in reserves, which do fluctuate, was the result of a special 
policy the petroleum sector pursued to encourage investment in 
oil and gas prospecting and production. He remarked that this 
policy resulted in the discovery of 70 new oil and natural gas 
reservoirs, 24 of which have already been placed on the 
production map. 
  He added that the increase was also the result of increasing 
efforts to develop productive wells by drilling intermediary 
wells, supporting the subsidiary production of water and gas, 
and the application of advanced technology. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

