<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Explains Egyptian Property Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Explains Egyptian Property Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   EA2605212394 Khartoum SUNA in Arabic 1700 GMT 26 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> EA2605212394 </F>
<F P=104>  Khartoum SUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Khartoum, 26 May (SUNA) -- The Foreign Ministry 
today issued a statement on allegations made by official media 
organs and the Government of Egypt concerning the directives 
issued by the authorities of the state of Khartoum on planning 
and reorganizing the national capital. 
  It said that these directives affect 16 places, including 
three properties belonging to the Egyptian Army which should 
have been returned to the Sudanese Government after the 
departure of the British-Egyptian occupying force at Sudan's 
independence in 1956. The other 13 areas were leased to the 
(?Irrigation Department) and to an Arab-Egyptian company which 
the government assigned for Egyptian and other resident 
communities in 1958. 
  The Ministry added in its statement that these places were 
unoccupied for a long period and claims that some families were 
evicted on the eve of the festival 'Id al-Adha are pure and 
unfounded distortions indulged in by newspapers. The ministry 
stressed that these directives were routine and also affected 
citizens, as well as Sudanese and foreign institutions. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

